
    ---------HTML : HYPER TEXT MARKUP LANGUAGE--------

    1. Markup Language : Set of rules used to display contents in a document
    2. HTML : used to create webpage
    3. HTML 5 : latest version
    4. HTML document : create file with html extension
        - It consist of tags ( <tag-name> )
        - HTML elements : starting-tag, content , ending-tag
        - Basic structure of html 
            <html>
                <head></head>
                <body></body>
            </html>
    5. HTML Attributes : properties of html tag, 
    6. Basic Tags
        - Heading : h1-h6 tag
        - Paragraph : p tag
        - Images : img tag
        - Form : form tag
        - Inputs : input tag with type (text,number,button,date,checkbox,radio)
        - Button : button
    7. Semantic tags : Improve SEO (Search Engine Optimisation) friendly website
        - example : header , nav , main , section, article, aside, footer etc.

    -----CSS : CASCADING STYLE SHEETS-----

    - Used to style html elements
    - Applying CSS into HTML elements
        - Inline CSS : add css code in html elements , using style attribute, Syntax : property:value;
        - Internal CSS : using style tag add style to html document 
        - Extenal CSS : using external css file to apply style to html document
    - CSS Syntax : 
        selector {
            property:value;
        }
    - CSS Selectors : 
        - Universal Selector (*) : used to select all tags
        - Element selector : using tag name
        - Id selector : using id attribute of html element
        - Class selector : using class attribute of a html element
    - Box model : Every element is placed inside a box in browser
        - Every Element = Content + padding + Border + Margin
        - Padding : space between content and Border
        - Margin : Outer Space of Border
    - Color - (name, hex code, rgb method)
    - Units - (px, %, em, rem)
    - Flexbox : used to display contents in row & column
        - Flex Container : display set as Flex
            - Justify content
            - Align items
        - Flex Items : 
    - Position : 
        - Static 
        - Fixed
        - Absolute
        - Relative
        - Sticky
    - CSS Grid : is a powerful 2-dimensional layout system used to create rows and columns easily.
        - properties : Parent tag
            - display : grid
    - A responsive website automatically adjusts its layout, images, text, and elements for different screen sizes: ✅ Mobile, ✅ Tablet, ✅ Laptop, ✅ Desktop
        - Different ways to make Responsive Website
            1. Add Viewport Meta Tag : This tells browser to match screen width.
            2. Use Flexible Widths : use unit as percent
            3. CSS Flexbox : use flex-wrap
            4. CSS Grid : use column width with auto-fit & minmax
            5. Using media queries in css
    - Media Queries : @media keyword, it can identify screen width, height, orientation & resolution
        - Screen Breakpoints
                /* Mobile */
                @media (max-width: 576px)

            /* Tablet */ 577 - 768px
            @media (max-width: 768px)

            /* Laptop */ 769 -992px
            @media (max-width: 992px)

            /* Desktop */ 
            @media (min-width: 1200px)

            - Syntax : @media  (media-feature: value) and (media-feature: value) {
        /* CSS rules to apply */
        }

        -----BOOTSTRAP : CSS FRAMEWORK-----

        1. Bootstrap is a popular front-end framework used to build responsive and mobile-friendly websites quickly.
        2. They uses , predefined class name, we can use the class name inorder to style webpage

        -----TAILWINDCSS : CSS FRAMEWORK-----

        1. To Add tailwind into a html page use its cdn script into head tag
        <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@tailwindcss/browser@4"></script>


        -----GIT & GITHUB-----

        1. Git is a Version Control System (VCS) used to track changes in code and collaborate with developers.
        2. Git Commands
            - git init : to create git inside a folder
            - git status : to check status of git 
            - git add . : used to add all untracked files into git
            - git commit -m "message" : used to save all added files into git
            - git remote origin url : used to link github repository with git
            - git push origin master : used to push all codes to github
        3. Hoisting page using Github : Inside github repository choose --> settings --> pages --> chhose branch as master --> save --> reload the page

        -----JAVASCRIPT-----

        1. Node.js is an open-source JavaScript runtime environment that allows you to run JavaScript outside the browser.
        2. Display contents : console.log()
        3. Variable : Used to store data
            - Variable created using :
                - var : ex: var variable-name = value
                - let : ex : let variable-name = value
                - const : ex: const variable-name = value
        4. Data types : define what kind of value a variable can store in JavaScript.
            - Two Main Categories
                1. Primitive Data Types - These store single values. ex : String, Number, Boolean, Undefined, Null
                2. Non-Primitive (Reference) Data Types - These store collections / references, ex: Object, Array, Function, Date
        5. Operators : 
            - Assignment Operators : =
            - Arithmetic Operators : + - % / * **
            - Relational Operators : > < <= >= == != ===
            - Logical Operators : && || !
            - Increment / Decrement Operators : ++ --
            - Shorthand Operators : += -= *= 
                a = a+10   similar to      a+=10
        6. Control structures : Used to take decision based on condition
            - if statements : Syntax - if(condition){ it executes when condition become true  }
            - if-else statements : : Syntax - if(condition){ it executes when condition become true  }else{
                it executes when condition become false
            }
            - else if ladder statements : multiple condition
        7. Looping statements : Used to repeat a task multiple times
            - while loop
            - for loop : Syntax - for(variable initialisation;condition;change variable){
                it executes when condition become true
            }
        8. Function : Used to perform specific task
            - Function Definition
                function function-name(arg1...){
                    steps to perform task
                    return statement used to return value to function call
                }
            - Function Call
                function-name(arg...)
        9. Arrays : used to store multiple values in a single variable
            - create Array : var/const/let variable-name = [item1,item2]
            - length : used to get total array items
            - index : used to get each item of array, it value starts from 0, usage : array-name[index]
            - for-of loop : used to get each array item one by one
                - Syntax : for(let variable-name of array-name){
                    task tobe repeated
                }
            - Array Methods : Syntax- array-name.method()
                - push() : Insert an item 
                - pop() : Remove last item from an array
                - map() : used to fetch each item of an array
                - filter(): used to check condition in an array
                - reduce(): used to find sum,largest/smallest values from an array
        10. Object : used to store multiple data as key-value pair in a single variable
            - create object : var/const/let variable-name = {key1:value1,key2:value2}, key must unique
            - Use key : to get value of an object
                - Syntax : object-name['key'] / object-name.key
        11. ES6 features of JS 
            - let and const : 
            - Arrow Functions : const function-name = (arg1,arg2..)=>{ function body } , Used to define function , Instead normal function Definition we can use Arrow function
            - Template Literals : Use backticks for dynamic strings.
                const name = "Nevin";
                console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
            - Spread/Rest Operators
                - The spread operator uses three dots ... to expand iterable values like arrays, strings, or objects into individual elements/properties.
                - The rest operator also uses three dots ..., but it does the opposite of spread. 
                    👉 Rest = Collect remaining values into one array/object
            - Destructuring : It means extracting values from arrays or objects and assigning them to variables
        12. Callback function : A callback function is a function passed as an argument to another function, and it is executed later.
            - Syntax : function-name(function Definition)
        13. DOM : Document Object Model
            - It is a programming interface that represents an HTML document as a tree of objects, so JavaScript can access and change webpage content, structure, and styles dynamically.
            - Use js in html document
                - Internal JS : using script tag we can add js code in html document
                - External JS : using external js to add js code , to link js with html using script tag
            - DOM Methods : used to access html elements by js
                - document.getElementByTag('tag')
                - document.getElementById('id') / simply use id inside js to access html element
                - document.getElementByClassName('class')
                - document.querySelectorAll('tag/#id/.className')
            - Events : actions perfromed by user
                - events are actions that happen in the browser and can be detected using JavaScript.
                - Common Webpage Events : Mouse Events, Keyboard Events, Form Events, Window / Browser Events
                - Event handling in html page : User Action → Event Occurs → JavaScript Responds
        14. Function Execution Model in JavaScript 
            - Synchronus function  : Executed using blocking model, first line executed only after next line executed
            - Asynchronous function : Executed using non-blocking model, it won't wait to complete execution of first function
                - Callback function, Nesting of callback leads to callback hell
                - Promise : A Promise is an object representing future success or failure of an async task.
                    - Promise States: Pending, Resolved (Fulfilled), Rejected
                    - To get resolved value use then method, to get reject value use catch method
                - Async/Await : use async keyword to a function, inside an Asynchronous function you can use await keyword
        15. API : Application Programming Interface
            - API is a way for two software systems to communicate with each other.
            - HTTP (Hyper text Transfer protocol) : HTTP is the protocol used for communication between a client (browser/app) and a server on the web.
                - HTTP 2 parts
                    - HTTP Header : 
                    - HTTP Body : share data
            - JSON : JavaScript Object Notation
                - JSON is a lightweight format used to store and exchange data in internet.
                - JSON is similar to Object, { "key":value }
            - URL : Uniform Resource Locator
                - ex: https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/1
                - Parts :
                    - Base url : https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com
                    - URI (Uniform Resource Identifier) : users
                    - parameters : 1
        16. API using JavaScript
            - Fetch method : return promise
        


